"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35110"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted with a two-day history of fever and right-sided abdominal pain. Her medical history includes type II diabetes, hypertension, myasthenia gravis and multiple resolved lower urinary tract infections. Her medications include ramipril and metformin. Her blood pressure is 95/70 mmHg, oxygen saturation at 94% on RA, pulse rate 120/min and temperature 38.4C. Her BMI is 32. She has cool peripheries, dry mucus membranes and is tender in the right upper quadrant. Her abdomen is otherwise soft with no signs of peritonism. An ultrasound examination is performed and a view of the right upper quadrant is shown (Image). As part of the sepsis protocol, intravenous antibiotics have been administered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotic regimens would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amoxicillin/clavulanate","Metronidazole","Piperacillin/tazobactam","Trimethoprim","Amoxicillin/Gentamicin/Metronidazole"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ultrasound shows a thick-walled gallbladder with a stone impacted in Hartmann\u0027s pouch. This finding confirms the clinical diagnosis of acute cholecystitis complicated by sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute cholecystitis is usually caused by Enterobacteriaceae(Gram-negative) and Enterococcus faecalis(Gran-positive). Amoxicillin and gentamicin cover both these Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria. Metronidazole has activity against anaerobic bacterial infections which constitutes the majority of intestinal flora. As with this patient, those with serious infections should have this form of triple antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, in this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Epiperacillin/tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as the patient has a history of myasthenia gravis which is a contraindication to using gentamicin due to the risk of prolonged neuromuscular blockade. Hence, an alternative antibiotic regimen will be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin/clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended by Australian guidelines as it has higher rates of resistance to some Gram-negative bacteria as compared to other antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E has activity against anaerobic bacterial infections but monotherapy is insufficient alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is usually used to treat urinary tract infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute cholecystitis is usually caused by Gram-negative Enterobacteriaceae and Gram-positive Enterococcus faecalis","Sepsis 6 protocol includes giving IV fluids, IV antibiotics, administering oxygen and measuring urinary output, checking lactate and taking blood cultures."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook [Internet]. Adelaide: AMH; c2020. Metronidazole [cited 2022 Feb 17]; [about 3 screens] . Available from: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.salus.idm.oclc.org/chapters/anti-infectives/antibacterials/other-antibacterials/metronidazole","Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care (ACSQHC). AURA 2017: second Australian report on antimicrobial use and resistance in human health. Sydney: ACSQHC; 2017.  https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/antimicrobial-use-and-resistance-in-australia/resources-page/.","Acute cholecystitis [published 2019 April]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au","Sepsis and septic shock from a biliary or gastrointestinal tract source [published 2019 April]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"782"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14410"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14410"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6b50f99a-841a-455e-b606-f642ccbcc3ef.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6b50f99a-841a-455e-b606-f642ccbcc3ef.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-04T09:40:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T17:09:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"782"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":